SIMPLE: stow
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stow
<hw>Stow</hw> <pr>(st⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stowed</conjf> <pr>(st⟦omac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Stowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stowen</ets>, fr. <ets>stowe</ets> a place, AS. <ets>stow</ets>;
cf. Icel. eld<ets>st⟦omac⟧</ets>a fireplace, hearth, OFries.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧</ets>, and E. <ets>stand</ets>. ⟦root⟧163.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To place or arrange in a compact mass; to put in its
proper place, or in a suitable place; to pack; <as>as, to
<ex>stow</ex>bags, bales, or casks in a ship's hold; to <ex>stow</ex>
hay in a mow; to <ex>stow</ex> sheaves</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some <qex>stow</qex> their oars, or stop the leaky sides.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put away in some place; to hide; to
lodge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Foul thief! where hast thou <qex>stowed</qex> my daughter?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To arrange anything compactly in; to fill, by
packing closely; <as>as, to <ex>stow</ex> a box, car, or the hold of a
ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stowage</ent>⟦br⟧
